title: crossbow
body:
A [[weapon]] consisting of a [[bow (weapon)|]] mounted on a stock that shoots projectiles, often called bolts or quarrels.

It works in much the same fashion as a regular bow, but replaces manual pulling of the bowstring with the use of a mechanical device, such as a lever or a crank, to draw back the string, allowing for more powerful shots in exchange for being quite slow to load and shoot in comparison to a regular bow.  Crossbows in general are easier to use than regular bows, which require more strength to pull back the bowstring.

title: fantastic_four_(2005)
body: Fantastic Four (sometimes stylized as Fantastic 4) is a 2005 American superhero film based on the Marvel Comics [[fantastic_four |team of the same name]], created by [[Stan Lee]] and Jack Kirby. It was directed by Tim Story, and released by 20th Century Fox. The film stars Ioan Gruffudd, Jessica Alba, [[Chris Evans]], Michael Chiklis, Julian McMahon, and Kerry Washington. The film follows the origins of the titular team as they learn to come into terms with their newfound abilities following their exposure to cosmic rays.

title: evo_moment_#37
body:
The moment at [[Evolution Championship Series|Evolution]] 2004's [[street_fighter_iii_(series)|Street Fighter III: 3rd Strike]] Loser's bracket final when [[Umehara Daigo]] (playing as [[ken masters|Ken]]) went against [[Justin Wong (gamer)|Justin Wong]] (playing as [[Chun-Li]]).

In the final round of match 1, Umehara's Ken was down to his last pixel of vitality. At this point, any special attack would knock Umehara's character out if connected, since special attacks deal chip damage even when blocked. In an attempt to win the round, Wong attempted to hit Umehara's Ken with Chun-Li's multihit Super Art move Houyoku-sen (鳳翼扇). 

However, instead of avoiding it, Umehara chose to "Parry," a technique whereby an incoming attack is blocked without the player losing any health, but doing so requires moving toward opponent's direction in the same time a hit lands, within 10 frames of the impact animation. After the move was launched, not only were all 15 hits Parried, but Umehara also managed to counter with a punishing combo that dealt just enough damage to win the match. 

This moment, and the ecstatic cheering of the spectators that followed, was recorded and later spread on the Internet, gaining immense popularity, and is often credited as one of the catalysts that popularized the competitive fighting game community.

Known in Japan as "[b]The Desperate Comeback[/b] (背水の逆転劇)" or "[b]Let's go Justin[/b]", a reference to a phrase yelled out by an unseen person in the crowd at the beginning of the full parry. Despite the name, the number #37 was arbitrarily added by the commentator Ben Cureton, who done so to signal the viewer that this is not the only "hype" moment during the tournament.

title: evolution_championship_series
body:
An [[eSports]] [[Fighting game]] tournament held annually in [[Las Vegas]], Nevada, [[United States]]. Generally considered the [i]de facto[/i] world championship for most fighting games, due to its large turnout.

h4. Notable events that have inspired fanart
* 2004: [[Evo Moment #37]], where during a [i][[Street Fighter III (series)|Street Fighter III]]: 3rd Strike[/i] match between [[Umehara Daigo]] and [[Justin Wong (gamer)|Justin Wong]], Umehara fully parries a [[Chun-Li]] super performed by Wong with little life left on his [[Ken Masters|Ken]], to turn the tables on Wong and win the round. The video of this moment and the wild crowd reaction to it became a viral hit on the Internet and inspires many tributes.
* 2013: The Evo organizers announce 7 games for the event, and announce an 8th game will be decided by a donation drive for cancer research, with the game whose community donates the most money getting the spot at the tournament. The two games raising the most money during the drive are [i][[Skullgirls]][/i] and [i][[Super Smash Bros.]] Melee[/i], with [i]Melee[/i] ultimately winning out and getting the spot in the tournament. 
* 2014: French player Luffy wins the [i][[street_fighter_iv_(series)|Ultra Street Fighter IV]][/i] tournament with [[Rose (Street Fighter)|Rose]], being the first non-Asian player to win an Evo [i]SFIV[/i] tournament. 
* 2015: During a [i][[Guilty Gear Xrd]][/i] match between Woshige and Ogawa, Woshige celebrates too early after winning a round and his unattended [[Millia Rage]] is swiftly beaten by Ogawa's [[Zato-1]] in the decisive round of the match.
* 2018: The first Evo event outside the United States is held in Tokyo, Japan as "Evo Japan 2018":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evo_Japan_2018.
* 2024: In a moment during a [i][[Street Fighter III (series)|Street Fighter III]]: 3rd Strike[/i] Losers Quarterfinals match popularly dubbed "[[EVO Moment #41]]", [[Hugo Andore|Hugo]] main [[Hayao (gamer)|]] managed to execute an air parry against FrankieBFG's Ken, then narrowly avoiding Ken's spinning kick with a Standing Heavy Kick (which is widely considered the worst nornal move in the game), and proceed to deal match-winning blow while living on the "magic pixel". Another notable moment within the match was when Hayao performed a [[split]] while playing the game.

title: c4
body:
A type of of plastic [[explosive]] (soft and moldable explosive) of the Composition C line of US-specified explosives consisting primarily of RDX.

C4 is very stable and insensitive to most physical shocks. C4 cannot be detonated by a gunshot or by dropping it onto a hard surface. It does not explode when set on fire or exposed to microwave radiation. Detonation can only be initiated by a combination of extreme heat and a shockwave, such as when a [[detonator]] inserted into it is fired.

C4 usually appears as a wrapped block of white substance, with popular culture depiction of the explosive often has some wiring or [[time bomb|timer]] rigged on it to trigger the [[explosion]].

h4. See also

A type of [[gameplay mechanics|gameplay mechanic]] involving players using certain currencies (either free or paid) to obtain randomized items or characters from a "gacha banner", similar to the [[gashapon]] random toy vending machine.

Several games (particularly free-to-play mobile games) have implemented this model as a method of obtaining rare items and are thus called [i]gacha[/i] games. Players often have a daily limit of free pulls they can make, with the ability to purchase more pulls with real world money.

body:
A poster distributed by [[police]] to warn the public about a criminal who is wanted for arrest. A wanted poster usually has the word "WANTED" at the top, and the fugitive's name and picture on the bottom. Sometimes a bounty or a list of their crimes is included.

In earlier times (or fictional settings), wanted posters would sometimes also read "wanted dead or alive", making the wanted criminal an outlaw in the literal sense (i.e. a person from whom the protection of the law was withdrawn and who could be killed without official repercussions by anyone).

title: coal
body:
A black or brownish-black combustible sedimentary rock, formed from subjecting the dead plant matter in peat to pressure and heat for millions of years. Coal is mostly carbon with variable amounts of other elements, chiefly hydrogen, sulfur, oxygen, and nitrogen. It is typically [[mining|mined]] to be used as a cheap, albeit [[pollution|polluting]], source of [[power plant|energy]] or for the production of steel.

title: zeong
body:
The [b]MSN-02 Zeong[/b] is a massive [[Mobile Suit]] [[mecha]] (often classified later as [[Mobile Armor]]) from the [[Gundam]] franchise. It first appeared in the [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] TV series from 1979.

The final Mobile Suit built by the Principality of [[Zeon]] during the One Year War, this revolutionary, monstrous unit developed specifically for Newtype use was only 80% complete when deployed into battle by [[Char Aznable]]. It famously has no legs, which is explained within the early series as due to the immense weight of the mobile suit meant that surface combat was deemed impossible as the suit would collapse upon itself. Its assets include powerful mega-particle cannons and detachable hands, each finger equipped with a cannon, remote-controlled via the innovative psycommu system.

The completed Zeong, referred to as the "[[Perfect Zeong]]", was later released in official material. This version notably has legs, contradicting the initial justification for the lack of one in the early series, though it is explained that it needed one specifically to aid in the weight balance of the mobile suit.

title: the_boys
body:
A raunchy, dark humor (and very violent) superhero [[parody]] comic book series created by Garth Ennis and Darrick Robertson. It ran from 2006 to 2012.

Set in a world where super-powered heroes exist [spoilers]thanks to Compound V, a special formula[/spoilers] created by the Vought corporation, it follows a team of vigilantes called The Boys, who combat and expose the crimes of "Supes" who secretly abused their powers against the public.

A live-action adaptation was released exclusively on Amazon Prime Video in 2019 and was praised as one of the few live-action comic book adaptations that is better than the comics. Unlike the comics which were criticized for being an edgy comic about Superheroes who are secretly horrible, the show instead explores current topics like corporate greed, bigotry, extremism, abuse of power and celebrity culture. The second season aired in 2020, the third season in 2022 and the fourth season in 2024. A fifth and final season is currently in the works.

The show has two spin-offs, [b]The Boys Presents: Diabolical[/b] an animated anthology series that was released in 2022, and [b]Gen V[/b], a spin-off set in The Boys universe that follows the students of Godolkin University, a special university for young Supes.

[b]Mexico[/b] (Spanish: México), officially the [b]United Mexican States[/b] ([i]Estados Unidos Mexicanos[/i]) is a country in North America. It is bordered to the north by the [[United States]]; to the south and west by the Pacific Ocean; to the southeast by [[Guatemala]], Belize, and the Caribbean Sea; and to the east by the Gulf of Mexico. title: devastator_(transformers)
body:
A character from the [[Transformers]] science fiction franchise.

[b]Devastator[/b] is an evil [i][[Constructicon]][/i] [[Decepticon]], a powerful, big and sentient green, grey, purple and black [[alien]] [[robot]] that results from the combination of six different construction-themed smaller robots.

Devastator is notable because he was the very first [i]combiner[/i] among the original Transformers. In [[Japan]] his name was changed to [b]Devastar[/b] (デバスター).

title: otto_octavius
body:
A ficticional character from the [[Marvel]] universe, also known as [[Doctor Octopus]].
The character was created by [[Stan Lee]] and Steve Ditko and first appeared in [[Spider-man (series)|The Amazing Spider-Man #3]] (July 1963). He is a highly intelligent, myopic, and stocky [[mad scientist]] who sports four strong and durable appendages resembling an octopus's tentacles, which extend from his body and can be used for various purposes. After his mechanical harness became permanently fused to his body during a lab accident, he turned to a life of crime, and came into conflict with the superhero [[Spider-Man]]. He has endured as one of Spider-Man's most prominent villains, and is regarded as one of his three archenemies, alongside the [[Green Goblin]] and [[Venom (marvel)|]]. He is the founder and leader of the Sinister Six, the first supervillain team to oppose Spider-Man.

Pertaining to the former [b]German Democratic Republic[/b] (in German: [i]Deutsche Demokratische Republik[/i]).

After [[World War II]], [[Germany]] was split into four occupation zones for the victorious Allied powers: the United States, United Kingdom, France and the Soviet Union. title: toy_packaging
body:
Packaging used to display a [[toy]] for sale in a [[shop]].

This is often of the form of a plastic clam-shell inside a [[cardboard box|cardboard]] [[box]] (common for e.g. [[figure]]s and [[doll]]s) with (or without) a window in the front, a plastic [[blister pack]] with a cardboard backing (common for e.g. smaller [[toy car]]s), or a thermally sealed [[plastic bag]].  In all cases, there will be the product name printed somewhere on the package, and possibly a UPC [[bar code]] or [[price tag]].

The contents may be an actual toy, a [[model kit]], an inanimate [[character doll]] or [[character charm|charm]], a miniaturized version of a living character ([[miniboy]] or [[minigirl]]), or possibly a scaled-up version of such a box with the actual living character inside.  In the latter two cases, the character might be described as [[encasement|encased]] or [[restrained]].

h4. Examples

* !post #5401837: A boxed clam-shell with a display widow
* !post #5216348: A printed cardboard box without a window
* !post #7618747: A blister pack with cardboard backing
* !post #6744990: A thermally sealed plastic bag

h4. See also

* [[box]] - any kind of cuboid container
** [[cardboard box]] - a box made of cardboard, usually unprinted, meant for e.g. shipping rather than sale as with this tag
** [[display case]] - a large box or cabinet for displaying something (usually glass)
** [[gift box]] - a nice box likely wrapped and perhaps with a bow or ribbon for presenting something as a gift
** [[toy box]] - a large chest or container for storing many toys (often in a child's bedroom or playroom)
* [[model kit]] - a set of plastic parts (usually combined on a [[sprue]]) to be assembled into a complete figure or model
* [[food packaging]]

title: ibuki_(azur_lane)
body:
[i][[Azur Lane]][/i]'s personification of the Japanese heavy cruiser [i]Ibuki[/i], as part of the [i][[World of Warships]][/i] collaboration. 
Character design by [[Maya G]], voiced by [[Fukuen Misato]].

Ibuki is a planned upgrade to the further [[Mogami (Azur Lane)|]]-class cruisers, she was also planned to be a light carrier in the midst of 1944. in her appearance, she is a Heavy Cruiser armed with 203mm Type 5 in twin turrets, only the noticable change is that her Auxillary armament of 100mm Type 98 Dual purpose artillery and the 40mm Type 5 Bofors which is capable of Air attacks and powerful than the Swedish Twin 40mm Bofors.

 
h4. Appearance
[tn]See gelbooru #4267965.[/tn]

She is portrayed with [[long hair|long]] [[blue hair]] with [[horns]], [[heterochromia]] eyes ([[red eyes|red on left]], [[blue eyes|blue on right]]), and [[large breasts]].

Her default outfit consists of a [[sideless outfit|sideless]] [[white dress]], white [[detached sleeves]], black [[thighhighs]], white [[platform footwear]], and a white [[hair ribbon]]. Her [[rigging]] consists of two separate pieces attached to her waist containing her five historical 20.3 cm twin gun mounts, 61 cm quad [[torpedo tubes]] concealed on the inner side of the hull rigs, two 10 cm twin [[anti-aircraft gun|DP mounts]] on where her rigs connect to the waist, and a [[katana]] attached to her left.

h4. History
Historically, [i]Ibuki[/i] and her sister, ultimately unnamed, were supposed to be successors to the [i]Mogami[/i]-class cruisers, with a similar armament. However, due to the increasingly dire wartime situation for Japan, [i]Ibuki[/i] was converted into a light aircraft carrier. The war came to an end before she could be completed, however, and she and her sister were scrapped on the slips shortly afterwards.

A [[vending machine]] that randomly dispenses encapsulated [[toy]]s or the rounded capsules themselves. 'Gashapon' is comprised of two Japanese onomatopoeia; 'gasha' for the sound of the crank on the vending machine, and 'pon' for the sound of the toy dropping into the receptacle. Also known as "gachapon" due to copyright reason, as the word "gashapon" was patented by [[Bandai]], the original creator of the machine.

A genre of mobile video games have emerged called [i][[gacha (game mechanic)|]] games[/i] ("gacha" being an alternate reading of "gasha") that use a similar randomized element. This tag refers to the physical machine, plastic capsule, and toy.

title: salamander_(game)
body:
[i][b]Salamander[/b][/i], retitled [i][b]Life Force[/b][/i] in North America and in the Japanese [[arcade]] re-release, is a [[science fiction]] 2D scrolling shooter arcade [[video game]] by [[Konami]]. 

Released in 1986 as a spin-off to [[Gradius]], Salamander introduced a simplified power-up system, two-player cooperative gameplay (using two [[starfighter]]s, the original [[Vic Viper]] and a new one called [[Lord British]]) and both horizontally and vertically scrolling stages. Some of these later became the norm for future Gradius games.

The game was ported to the [[Famicom]] and the [[NES]] a year later. It also has been released on the Amstrad CPC, Commodore 64 and ZX Spectrum, the NEC [[Pc Engine]], the [[Sony]] [[PlayStation 1]], the [[Sega Saturn]], on mobile phones, the [[PlayStation Portable]] and the [[PlayStation 4]] in the last years. 

Salamander was followed with an official sequel in 1996 entitled [[Salamander 2]].

title: gerwalk
body:
[b]GERWALK[/b] ([b]G[/b]round [b]E[/b]ffective [b]R[/b]einforcement of [b]W[/b]inged [b]A[/b]rmament with [b]L[/b]ocomotive [b]K[/b]nee-joint) is a [[VTOL]] transformation mode of the [[VF-1]] [[variable fighter]] from [[MACROSS]] (and other related transformable [[mecha]]) where the nose and wings of the fighter [[jet]] are stuck on "chicken [[walker (robot)|]]" legs with two arms. The legs are formed by the aircraft's engines and intakes, bent down and forward. The arms are stored between the engines in fighter mode and fold out to the sides, reaching around from behind the legs.

Legend tells that when [[Kawamori Shouji]] first designed the VF-1 [i]Valkyrie[/i], he did not include this mode initially at all. However, after receiving a prototype of a toy based in the VF-1 he noticed that the legs of the figure were very very loose and constantly fell down during transformation into jet mode, so it resembled a unused walker mecha design called "Gawalk" that he developed years before for another show. Thus he adopted the mode in the mecha and changed its name into "Gerwalk" afterwards. 

h4.Other mecha that feature this mode

* The [[orguss_(mecha)|Orguss]] from [[Choujikuu Seiki Orguss]].
* The [[Legioss]] from [[Kikou Souseiki Mospeada]].
* The [[TASC-01-SCF_Logan|Logan]] and the [[Spartas]] from [[Choujikuu Kidan Southern Cross]].
* [[Opa-Opa]] from the [[Fantasy Zone]] [[video game]] series. 
* The [[mr._heli_(mecha)|titular mecha helicopter]] from the [[Mr. HELI]] 1987 video game.

title: du_fu
body:
Du Fu (Pinyin: Dù Fǔ, Wade-Giles: Tu Fu; Japanese: To Ho; 712–770) 

A [[China|Chinese]] scholar-official and poet of the Tang Dynasty, whose minor career in civil service was cut permanently short due to the An Lushan Rebellion in 755, at which point he took up a reclusive lifestyle much like his elder contemporary, [[Li Bai]]. 

Unlike Li, his reputation at home and abroad took off only in the centuries following his death, but the two are now both considered to be the greatest poets of the Tang, and among the greatest in the Chinese literary canon. 

Would become the subject of the [[meme]] "[i][[Du fu hen mang]][/i]", as well as being [[du fu (sangai senki)|reimagined as a female character]] in the game [[Sangai Senki]].

title: candy_gore
body:
Genre of [[guro]]-adjacent art that depicts violence and gore in brightly colored, dream-like, sugary scenes. Various sweets are often used as replacements for organs, and blood is often an unnatural color (either bright or pastel), and may sparkle. Despite the name, it is not limited to only involving [[candy]], as [[fruit]] and [[cake]] are also often used, such as having a character being cut open to reveal one of the two inside.

When not directly involving food, the genre stays very detached from any sense of realism - blood will be thick, shiny and gooey, and often shown dripping between perfectly neat segmented slices of flesh. Realistic guro with discolored blood would not qualify for this tag, and a lot of this tag would not qualify for guro due to its unrealistic nature.

title: lilith_(evangelion)
body:
The second [[angel_(evangelion)|angel]] from [[Neon Genesis Evangelion]] who initially appears as a white, legless giant, whose face is covered with a mask displaying the logo of [[Seele (evangelion)|]]. Numerous human-like legs protrude from its legless stumps, it was at first thought to be [[Adam (evangelion)|]] and is usually seen stuck to a [[crucifix]] and bleeding [[LCL]]. 

Not to be confused with [[Lilith (Ayanami Rei)]], which refers to the all-white giant [[Ayanami Rei|Rei]] version which appears in [[The End of Evangelion]]. 

[spoilers]Later in the series it is revealed that all human beings are the spawn of Lilith, and that humanity as a whole is actually the 18th angel, [b]Lilin[/b].[/spoilers]

See also [[Black Moon Lilith]]

title: angel_(evangelion)
body:
A set of seventeen (possibly eighteen) varied, generally antagonistic, very powerful and very bizarre looking [[alien]] [[monster|beings]] in [[Neon Genesis Evangelion]].

In [[real life]] they serve as [i]monster of the week[/i] for the original animated TV series. Most of their designs are based in [[biblically accurate angel|the original scary and very bizarre depictions]] of [[Angel]]s in the [[christianity|Christian]] [[The Bible|Bible]]. [spoilers]As the series progresses it is revealed that the Angels are artificially engineered lifeforms created by ancient intelligent alien beings to become the top dominating species in the different inhabited planets of [[milky_way|our galaxy]].[/spoilers]

h4. List of Angels

h6. 1st - [[Adam (evangelion)|]]

* A giant being of light (roughly EVA-shaped with dark spots where its eyes and core would assumed to be).
* An embryonic form, typically set either subdermally in a person's palm/hand or in a solid, orange, transparent material.
* [spoilers]Its remains were studied by [[Ikari Gendou]] and served as basis to develop the [[evangelion_(mecha)|Evangelions]].[/spoilers] 

h6. 2nd - [[Lilith (evangelion)|]]

* A large, pudgy, white being with a seven-eyed mask over its face and a lower body composed of several human-sized (lower) bodies, [[crucifixion|crucified]] to a red cross by the [[Lance of Longinus (Evangelion)|]].
* If the Lance is not present, then the lower body may feature full legs, but still with smaller bodies poking out.
* A form of [spoiler][[Lilith (Ayanami Rei)|Ayanami Rei]], marked by being giant, naked, white, and winged; sometimes seen as large body parts in the background, most notably a giant face.[/spoiler]

h6. 3rd - [[Sachiel (evangelion)|]]

* Vaguely humanoid creature with large bony structures on its shoulders and torso and a distinctive beaked face.

h6. 4th - [[Shamshel (evangelion)|]]

* Vaguely arthropod-like creature, with a long cylindrical body, a roughly shovel-shaped head with two eyespot-like markings.

h6. 5th - [[Ramiel (evangelion)|]]

* A hollow, translucent blue octahedron.

h6. 6th - [[Gaghiel (evangelion)|]]

* An aquatic being with a massive body and long jaws filled with sharp teeth.

h6. 7th - [[Israfel (evangelion)|]]

* Has the appearance of a massive, vaguely humanoid creature, its most notable weapon is its ability to split itself into separate, twin Angels.

h6. 8th - [[Sandalphon (evangelion)|]]

* Looks similar in form to a flatfish, but with two arm-like appendages and two knobs on its "top" side.

h6. 9th - [[Matariel]]

* Has the appearance of a massive arachnid-like creature with numerous eyes.

h6. 10th - [[Sahaquiel (evangelion)|]]

* A massive and bizarrely-shaped creature. It has an elongated body, with three eye-like markings.

h6. 11th - [[Iruel]]

* A nano-scale entity, the Angel seems to simply spread by rapidly reproducing at the cellular level.

h6. 12th - [[Leliel (evangelion)|]]

* Appears as a large, floating, black-and-white patterned sphere. [spoiler]A transdimensional being, the shadow below the sphere is the actual form of the angel.[/spoiler]

h6. 13th - [[Bardiel (evangelion)|]]

* Since it inhabits [[EVA 03]], it looks like it as well, only with a dark blue body, and longer arms.

h6. 14th - [[Zeruel (evangelion)|]]

* A floating creature as large as the Evas but lacking humanoid limbs, and possessing folding foil-like "arms" and a malformed "skull" as a face.

h6. 15th - [[Arael]]

* The form of a massive, glowing winged creature.

h6. 16th - [[Armisael (evangelion)|]]

* Appears as a large glowing floating torus (3 dimensional circle).
* A double helix structure.
* Or a single thread.

h6. 17th - Tabris

* Appears to be a pale human male with white hair, red eyes, and dressed in typical school attire; often smiling.
* A genderswap of the above, with no pants, twintails, and a set of six feathered wings.
* [spoiler][[Nagisa Kaworu]][/spoiler]

h6. 18th - Lilin

* [spoilers]The spawn of [[Lilith (evangelion)|]], also known as [i]Homo Sapiens[/i]. Mankind/Humanity as a whole is the final Angel.[/spoilers]

title: tumblr_sexyman_tournament
body:
A Twitter tournament based around the [[meme]] discussing the trend of unconventional-looking characters being considered attractive and popular that started on [[Tumblr]], often to the bewilderment of other websites, said sites having joined in since.

The tournament itself was held on September 6th, 2022, ending with the final match between [[Sans (undertale)|]] from [i][[Undertale]][/i] and [[Reigen Arataka]] from [i][[Mob Psycho 100]][/i]. Reigen had, leading up to the tournament, won two other tournaments declaring him both "Twink Supreme":https://twitter.com/lgbtbeam/status/1565399868402696192 and the "Ultimate DILF":[https://twitter.com/denjictrl/status/1567125015656628225], so voting for this finale was intense. Sans would ultimately beat Reigen out by 0.1%, to mass celebration. Several memes would spawn out of this, from [[Elizabeth II]] passing away in the meantime being attributed to the intensity of the finale, to Toby Fox himself "writing":https://twitter.com/tobyfox/status/1567739718762364929 a scene depicting the ending. Reigen would then go on to win the "Superior MILF":[https://twitter.com/scrtvplotter/status/1567954322566295553], the "Hottest Anime Woman":[https://twitter.com/genicecream/status/1568754222312861696], and the "True Babygirl":[https://twitter.com/ranpoedgw/status/1568792119141347328] in three other tournaments. This would then ultimately be capped off with the official Undertale x Requiem Café event in Anaheim, California serving the unofficial "Reigen Supreme" "drink":https://twitter.com/kellyonelani/status/1575712882423083008 for $4.20 after running out of "Sans Soda".

The tournament was later rerun on Tumblr, and won by Cecil Palmer from [[Welcome to Night Vale]].

title: holy_roman_empire
body:
[b]The Holy Roman Empire[/b], also known as [b]The First Reich[/b] or [b]The Holy Roman Empire of the [[germany|German]] Nation[/b] after 1512, was a polity in Central and Western Europe, usually headed by the Holy Roman emperor. It developed in the [[medieval|Early Middle Ages]] and lasted for almost one thousand years until its dissolution in 1806 during the Napoleonic Wars.

On 25 December 800, Pope Leo III crowned Frankish king [[Charlemagne]] as Roman emperor, reviving the title in Western Europe more than three centuries after the fall of the ancient Western [[Roman Empire]] in 476. The title lapsed in 924, but was revived in 962 when [[Otto I]] was crowned emperor by Pope John XII, fashioning himself as Charlemagne's and the Carolingian Empire's successor, and beginning a continuous existence of the empire for over eight centuries.

From 962 until the twelfth century, the empire was the most powerful monarchy in Europe. The functioning of government depended on the harmonious cooperation between emperor and vassals; this harmony was disturbed during the Salian period. The empire reached the apex of territorial expansion and power under the House of Hohenstaufen in the mid-thirteenth century, but overextension led to a partial collapse.

While the office of emperor had been reestablished, the exact term for his realm as the "Holy Roman Empire" was not used until the 13th century. A process of Imperial Reform in the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries transformed the empire, creating a set of institutions which endured until its final demise in the nineteenth century. On 6 August 1806, Emperor Francis II dissolved the empire following the creation – the month before, by [[france|French]] emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] – of the Confederation of the Rhine, a confederation of German client states loyal not to the Holy Roman emperor but to France.

title: suuankou
body:
One of the yakuman (highest-scoring) hands in [[mahjong]]. Known in English as "Four Concealed Triplets". 

Comes in two variants: suuankou-shanpon, where three of the triplets are in the hand, the wait is on a tile to complete either of the two remaining pairs, and you have to complete that set wait yourself to count as suuankou (lest it'll count only as toitoihou and san'ankou, plus whatever extra value the tiles/hand have); and suuankou-tanki (occasionally valued as double yakuman), where the four triplets are in the hand, the wait is on a single tile to complete the pair, and you can complete that single wait from another player yet it'll still count as suuankou.

title: aren't_grim_reapers_supposed_to_be_scary
body:
Visual novel created by the artist and animator [[Kamuo]].

The plot focuses on a young man, who apparently died in unknown circumstances, having zero memories or recollections of the past. Accepting his fate, and ready for the eternal rest, he slowly wakes up in a mysterious reality, surrounded of cute girls claiming to be grim reapers. Naturally confused, but having no reasons to doubt them, the protagonist wants answers, nevertheless, the grim reapers are as confused as him about why he came to their dimension, or who is him in the first place. The only option left to get the answers he wants, is accept the help of the grim reapers and their conditions to understand who, or what he is.

The last official update of the game was released during April, 2022. Since then, no official updates for the game has been released, and the creator declared he is not satisfied with his own visual novel. And while he was willing to continue the project, he was simply not happy with the art and the direction of the game mechanics, so he was re-working on the game from zero, hoping to get better results. Currently, the game is still on hiatus, and its future is still unknown.

title: suzumiya_haruhi
body:
Titular main character of [[Suzumiya Haruhi no Yuuutsu]]. A spunky, demanding teenage girl who loves mysteries and paranormal phenomena. 

[spoiler]Unbeknowst to Haruhi, she has the ability to alter the very fabric of reality itself to get whatever she wished for, including an encounter with [[Nagato Yuki|an alien]], a [[Asahina Mikuru|time traveller]], and an [[Koizumi Itsuki|esper]] who were sent to investigate her.[/spoiler]

She has [[brown eyes]] and a [[medium hair|medium-length]] [[brown hair|brown]] [[bob cut]], which she wears with a [[orange hairband]]. Her most common outfit is a blue [[serafuku]] with a [[red ribbon]] and [[black socks|black]] [[kneehighs]].

She is voiced by [[Hirano Aya]] in Japanese and [[Wendee Lee]] in English.
